      "content": "You can explain that substantive due process serves as a vital safeguard against tyranny by protecting unenumerated rights—those not specifically written in the Constitution. It acts as a check on legislative power, asserting that the government cannot infringe upon core human liberties simply because the Constitution doesn't explicitly forbid the action. While some critics label this \"judicial activism,\" proponents argue it is the constitutional mechanism that allows the law to evolve and protect fundamental dignity against shifting societal norms.",
